Data analysis

Table

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.75) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.14. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.88 (S.E. = 3.22, p < .001, 95% CI [8.58, 21.19]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.07, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.206, 95% CI [-0.04, 0.17]; Std. beta = 0.26, 95% CI [-0.14, 0.67])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.84, S.E. = 1.54, p = 0.585, 95% CI [-3.85, 2.17]; Std. beta = -0.23, 95% CI [-1.07, 0.61])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.18, S.E. = 1.13, p = 0.875, 95% CI [-2.40, 2.04]; Std. beta = -0.05, 95% CI [-0.67, 0.57])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.55, S.E. = 1.60, p = 0.027, 95% CI [0.41, 6.69]; Std. beta = 0.99, 95% CI [0.12, 1.87])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
